3️⃣ Idempotency — Prevent Double Transfer
🔴 Problem

Same transfer request may be sent multiple times due to:

Network timeout

User double-click

Payment gateway retry

Service crash

Client retry logic

Without idempotency:

Transfer ₹1000
→ processed twice
→ double debit ❌

🟢 Definition

Idempotency = Same request executed many times → same result (only one actual transfer).

🧠 Key Idea

Each request must contain unique Idempotency Key (Request ID)

Example:

X-Idempotency-Key: TXN-USER1-000123


Server stores this key and ensures it is processed only once.

🔄 Flow
1. Client sends transfer with idempotency_key
2. Server checks DB:

   If key exists → return previous result
   If key not exists → process transfer

3. Save idempotency_key + response

🗄️ Table Design
idempotency_records
Column	Description
idempotency_key (PK)	Unique request id
status	SUCCESS / FAILED
response	Stored API response
created_at	timestamp

Important: Add UNIQUE constraint on idempotency_key.

💸 Transaction Flow with Idempotency
BEGIN TRANSACTION

1. Check idempotency_key exists?
      YES → return stored result
      NO  → continue

2. Lock sender account
3. Validate balance
4. Debit sender
5. Credit receiver
6. Insert transaction record
7. Save idempotency record

COMMIT


If failure → ROLLBACK → key not stored → safe retry.

🧩 Spring Boot Concept
Check before processing
Optional<IdempotencyRecord> record =
        repo.findById(req.getRequestId());

if (record.isPresent()) {
    return deserialize(record.get().getResponse());
}

Save after success
IdempotencyRecord rec = new IdempotencyRecord();
rec.setIdempotencyKey(req.getRequestId());
rec.setStatus("SUCCESS");
rec.setResponse(serialize(response));
repo.save(rec);

⚠️ Concurrency Case (Important)

Two same requests arrive at same time:

Solution:

Put UNIQUE constraint on idempotency_key

Wrap in @Transactional

One insert succeeds, second fails → fetch stored result

